01:50:54.550 --> 01:50:59.550
They're important in coordinating
signals across neurons.

01:50:59.945 --> 01:51:03.500
Just like in a computer, a computer steps.

01:51:03.500 --> 01:51:06.290
So, a computer knows when
information is coming

01:51:06.290 --> 01:51:08.200
from another part of a computer

01:51:08.200 --> 01:51:11.930
so that it was originated
at a particular time.

01:51:11.930 --> 01:51:14.530
And so, that the screen
by step-by-step thing

01:51:14.530 --> 01:51:16.020
is important in computer control.

01:51:16.020 --> 01:51:18.037
Now, the brain is not a digital device,

01:51:18.037 --> 01:51:20.010
and it's an analog device,

01:51:20.010 --> 01:51:24.880
but when I have a signal that's
coming in my ear and my eye,

01:51:24.880 --> 01:51:26.447
which is Andrew Huberman speaking

01:51:26.447 --> 01:51:30.400
and I'm looking at his
face, I see that as a whole,

01:51:30.400 --> 01:51:33.050
but the signal is coming into
different parts of my brain.

01:51:33.050 --> 01:51:34.800
How do I unify that?

01:51:34.800 --> 01:51:38.205
Well, my neurons are
very sensitive to changes

01:51:38.205 --> 01:51:42.000
in signals arriving by
fractions of a millisecond.

01:51:42.000 --> 01:51:43.870
So, I know we're sure that those signals

01:51:43.870 --> 01:51:47.280
coming in represent the same signal.

01:51:47.280 --> 01:51:49.150
Well, if I have throughout my brain

01:51:49.150 --> 01:51:53.990
and isolation and the signals
ride on that oscillation,

01:51:53.990 --> 01:51:55.920
let's say the peak of the oscillation,

01:51:55.920 --> 01:51:58.480
I can then have a much better handle

01:51:58.480 --> 01:52:00.367
on the road of timing and say,

01:52:00.367 --> 01:52:03.060
"Those two signals came
in at the same time.

01:52:03.060 --> 01:52:05.410
They may relate to the
same object and ah ha,

01:52:05.410 --> 01:52:10.410
I see you as one unified
thing spouting talking."

01:52:10.490 --> 01:52:13.083
And so, these oscillations come

01:52:13.083 --> 01:52:16.540
in many different frequency ranges

01:52:16.540 --> 01:52:18.810
and are important in memory formation

01:52:18.810 --> 01:52:21.020
and all sorts of things.

01:52:21.020 --> 01:52:22.738
I don't think people pay
much attention to breathing

01:52:22.738 --> 01:52:27.106
because it's relatively slow to the range

01:52:27.106 --> 01:52:30.510
when you think about milliseconds,

01:52:30.510 --> 01:52:33.937
but we have important
things that are thought

01:52:33.937 --> 01:52:36.520
to be important in cognitive function,

01:52:36.520 --> 01:52:39.450
which are a few cycles per second

01:52:39.450 --> 01:52:42.510
to 20, 30, 40, 50 cycles per second.

01:52:42.510 --> 01:52:46.660
Breathing in humans is
maybe .2 cycles per second,

01:52:46.660 --> 01:52:47.700
every five seconds.

01:52:47.700 --> 01:52:51.120
Although in rodents they're
up to four per second,

01:52:51.120 --> 01:52:53.160
which is pretty fast.

01:52:53.160 --> 01:52:57.870
So, but breathing has one
thing which is special,

01:52:57.870 --> 01:53:00.470
that is you can readily change it.

01:53:00.470 --> 01:53:03.090
So, the degree to which the brain is using

01:53:03.090 --> 01:53:05.493
that slow signal for anything,

01:53:06.360 --> 01:53:09.923
if that becomes part of its
