01:58:03.028 --> 01:58:05.430
or what would you like to see more of

01:58:05.430 --> 01:58:09.083
in terms of exploration of
breathwork and what do you do?

01:58:11.160 --> 01:58:16.160
- Well, I'm a relatively
new convert to breathwork.

01:58:16.503 --> 01:58:19.225
Through my own investigation of it,

01:58:19.225 --> 01:58:22.330
I became convinced that it's real,

01:58:22.330 --> 01:58:27.330
and I'm basically a beginner
in terms of my own practice.

01:58:28.420 --> 01:58:32.030
And I like to keep things simple,

01:58:32.030 --> 01:58:35.030
and I think I've discussed this before.

01:58:35.030 --> 01:58:37.580
I liken it to someone who's a couch potato

01:58:37.580 --> 01:58:39.800
who was told they got
to begin to exercise.

01:58:39.800 --> 01:58:42.100
You don't go out and run a marathon.

01:58:42.100 --> 01:58:44.240
So, couch potato, you say,

01:58:44.240 --> 01:58:47.020
okay, get up and walk for
five minutes and 10 minutes.

01:58:47.020 --> 01:58:49.910
And then, okay, now you're
walking for a longer period.

01:58:49.910 --> 01:58:53.760
You'll begin to run, and
then you reach a point,

01:58:53.760 --> 01:58:57.040
you say, well, gee, I'm
interested in this sport.

01:58:57.040 --> 01:58:58.775
And there may be particular
kinds of practices

01:58:58.775 --> 01:59:01.363
that you can use that could be helpful

01:59:01.363 --> 01:59:04.880
in optimizing performance of that sport.

01:59:04.880 --> 01:59:06.420
I'm not there yet.

01:59:06.420 --> 01:59:09.160
I find I get tremendous benefit

01:59:09.160 --> 01:59:11.730
by relatively short periods

01:59:11.730 --> 01:59:15.900
between five and maybe 20 minutes

01:59:15.900 --> 01:59:17.273
of doing box breathing.

01:59:18.250 --> 01:59:20.310
It's very simple to do.

01:59:20.310 --> 01:59:24.890
I have a simple app, which
helps me keep the timing.

01:59:24.890 --> 01:59:26.010
- Do you recall which app it is?

01:59:26.010 --> 01:59:27.570
Is it the Apnea Trainer?

01:59:27.570 --> 01:59:28.403
Is that the one?

01:59:28.403 --> 01:59:30.183
- Well, I was using Calm for a long time,

01:59:30.183 --> 01:59:32.296
but I let my subscription lapse

01:59:32.296 --> 01:59:37.296
and I have another one whose
name I don't remember but it's,

01:59:37.640 --> 01:59:40.920
so it's very simple and it works for me.

01:59:40.920 --> 01:59:45.300
I'm now trying this Tummo,
because I'm just curious

01:59:45.300 --> 01:59:47.587
and exploring it because it may be acting

01:59:47.587 --> 01:59:49.057
for a different way and I want to see

01:59:49.057 --> 01:59:52.173
if I respond differently.

01:59:54.427 --> 01:59:57.300
So, I don't have a
particular point of view.

01:59:57.300 --> 01:59:59.400
Now, I have friends and colleagues

01:59:59.400 --> 02:00:03.640
who are into particular
styles like Wim Hof.

02:00:03.640 --> 02:00:05.801
And I think what he's doing is great

02:00:05.801 --> 02:00:08.750
and getting people who are interested.

02:00:08.750 --> 02:00:11.800
I think the notion is that I would like

02:00:11.800 --> 02:00:16.520
to see more people exploring
this and to some degree,

02:00:16.520 --> 02:00:19.050
as you point out, 30 minutes a day,

02:00:19.050 --> 02:00:24.050
some of the breath patterns
that some of these stars

02:00:24.460 --> 02:00:29.100
like Wim Hof are a little
intimidating to newbies.

02:00:29.100 --> 02:00:31.600
And so, I would like to
see something very simple,

02:00:31.600 --> 02:00:33.290
that what I tell my friends is, look,

02:00:33.290 --> 02:00:34.710
just try it five or 10 minutes.

02:00:34.710 --> 02:00:37.170
See if you feel better,
do it for a few days.

02:00:37.170 --> 02:00:40.120
If you don't like it, stop
it, it doesn't cost anything.

02:00:40.120 --> 02:00:43.900
And invariably, they
find that it's helpful.

02:00:43.900 --> 02:00:47.600
I will often interrupt my day

02:00:51.420 --> 02:00:52.800
to take five or 10 minutes.

02:00:52.800 --> 02:00:54.790
Like, if I find that I'm lagging...

02:00:56.446 --> 02:00:59.050
I think there's some pretty good data

02:00:59.050 --> 02:01:03.610
that your performance
after lunch declines.

02:01:03.610 --> 02:01:06.290
And so, very often what
I'll do after lunch,

02:01:06.290 --> 02:01:08.477
which I didn't do today
is take five or 10 minutes

02:01:08.477 --> 02:01:10.276
and just sort of breath practice.

02:01:10.276 --> 02:01:13.440
- And lately, what does that
breath practice look like?

02:01:13.440 --> 02:01:15.497
- It's just box breathing
for five to 10 minutes.

02:01:15.497 --> 02:01:17.860
- And the duration of
your inhales and holds

02:01:17.860 --> 02:01:19.750
and exhales and holds is set by the app?

02:01:19.750 --> 02:01:20.583
Is that right?

02:01:20.583 --> 02:01:22.970
- Well, I do five seconds.

02:01:22.970 --> 02:01:25.740
- So, five seconds
inhale, five second hold,

02:01:25.740 --> 02:01:27.580
five second, exhale, five second hold.

02:01:27.580 --> 02:01:30.040
- Yeah, and sometimes I'll do doubles.

02:01:30.040 --> 02:01:35.040
I'll do 10 seconds just
because I get bored.

02:01:35.423 --> 02:01:39.677
It's just, I feel like doing
it and it's very helpful.

02:01:42.480 --> 02:01:43.313
I mean...

02:01:44.440 --> 02:01:45.876
Now, that's not the only thing I do

02:01:45.876 --> 02:01:49.660
with respect to trying to
maintain my sanity and my health.

02:01:49.660 --> 02:01:51.570
- No, I can imagine there'd
be a number of things,

02:01:51.570 --> 02:01:55.360
although, because you seem
very sane and very healthy,

02:01:55.360 --> 02:01:57.927
I in fact, know that you
are both of those things.

02:01:57.927 --> 02:01:59.313
- Right, you suspect that I am.

02:01:59.313 --> 02:02:01.833
- I suspect that there's data.

02:02:03.640 --> 02:02:07.140
Awhile back we had a conversation,
a casual conversation,

02:02:07.140 --> 02:02:09.000
but you said something that
really stuck in my mind,

02:02:09.000 --> 02:02:11.370
which is that it might be

02:02:11.370 --> 02:02:14.763
that the specific pattern of breathwork

02:02:14.763 --> 02:02:18.390
that one does is not as important

02:02:18.390 --> 02:02:22.470
as experiencing transitions
between states based

02:02:22.470 --> 02:02:25.690
on deliberate breathwork or
something to that extent,

02:02:25.690 --> 02:02:28.830
which I interpreted to mean that if I were

02:02:28.830 --> 02:02:30.940
to do box breathing with five second in,

02:02:30.940 --> 02:02:32.960
five seconds hold, five second exhale,

02:02:32.960 --> 02:02:35.200
five second hold for a couple of days,

02:02:35.200 --> 02:02:36.940
or maybe even a couple of
minutes and then switch

02:02:36.940 --> 02:02:39.660
to 10 seconds or then switch to Tummo,

02:02:39.660 --> 02:02:42.030
that there's something powerful perhaps

02:02:42.030 --> 02:02:46.110
in the transitions and
realizing the relationship

02:02:46.110 --> 02:02:47.460
between different patterns of breathing

02:02:47.460 --> 02:02:48.320
in those transitions,

02:02:48.320 --> 02:02:50.042
much in the same way that you can get

02:02:50.042 --> 02:02:53.650
into one of these cars
at an amusement park

02:02:53.650 --> 02:02:56.130
that just goes at a constant
rate and then stops.

02:02:56.130 --> 02:02:58.683
Very different than
learning how to shift gears.

02:02:59.600 --> 02:03:00.500
I used to drive a manual.

02:03:00.500 --> 02:03:02.650
I still can so I'm thinking
about a manual transmission,

02:03:02.650 --> 02:03:04.290
but even with an automatic transmission,

02:03:04.290 --> 02:03:07.250
you start to get a sense
of how the vehicle behaves

02:03:07.250 --> 02:03:08.850
under different conditions.

02:03:08.850 --> 02:03:11.310
And I thought that was a beautiful seed

02:03:11.310 --> 02:03:13.030
for a potential breathwork practice

02:03:13.030 --> 02:03:14.370
that at least to my awareness,

02:03:14.370 --> 02:03:16.060
nobody has really formalized,

02:03:16.060 --> 02:03:17.984
which is that you
introduce some variability

02:03:17.984 --> 02:03:20.810
within the practice that's somewhat random

02:03:20.810 --> 02:03:23.160
in order to be able to
sense the relationship

02:03:23.160 --> 02:03:25.360
between different speeds
and depths of inhales,

02:03:25.360 --> 02:03:27.070
exhales and holds and so forth.

02:03:27.070 --> 02:03:29.060
And essentially, it's like
driving around the track,

02:03:29.060 --> 02:03:31.930
but with obstacles at different rates

02:03:31.930 --> 02:03:33.980
and breaking and restarting
and things of that sort,

02:03:33.980 --> 02:03:35.830
that's how you learn how to drive.

02:03:35.830 --> 02:03:39.790
What do you think about that
and if you like it enough,

02:03:39.790 --> 02:03:41.600
can we call it the Feldman protocol?

02:03:41.600 --> 02:03:42.700
- Oh, please [laughs].

02:03:45.250 --> 02:03:48.450
I was asked in this BBC interview once why

02:03:48.450 --> 02:03:50.283
didn't I name it the Feldman complex,

02:03:50.283 --> 02:03:51.920
instead of pre-Botzinger complex?

02:03:51.920 --> 02:03:54.090
- You said I already
have a Feldman complex.

02:03:54.090 --> 02:03:56.390
- Well, it sounds like
a psychiatric disorder,

02:03:57.532 --> 02:04:02.532
but I think the primary effect
is this disruptive effect,

02:04:04.610 --> 02:04:05.843
which I described,

02:04:06.820 --> 02:04:11.820
but the particular responses
may clearly vary depending

02:04:12.640 --> 02:04:14.593
on what that disruption is.

02:04:15.800 --> 02:04:18.580
I don't know of any particular data,

02:04:18.580 --> 02:04:20.990
which are as in well
controlled experiments,

02:04:20.990 --> 02:04:24.202
which can actually work
through the different types

02:04:24.202 --> 02:04:27.510
of breathing patterns or
simply with a box pattern,

02:04:27.510 --> 02:04:29.830
just varying the durations.

02:04:29.830 --> 02:04:32.130
I mean, pranayama is sort of similar,

02:04:32.130 --> 02:04:34.160
but the amount of time you spend

02:04:34.160 --> 02:04:35.860
going around the box is different.

02:04:36.810 --> 02:04:38.810
So, I don't really have
much to say about this.

02:04:38.810 --> 02:04:43.610
I mean, this is why we need
better controlled experiments

02:04:43.610 --> 02:04:47.430
in humans and I think
this is where being able

02:04:47.430 --> 02:04:50.220
to study in rodents where you can have

02:04:50.220 --> 02:04:53.937
a wide range of perturbations

02:04:55.593 --> 02:04:58.410
while you're doing more invasive studies

02:04:58.410 --> 02:05:01.670
to really get down as to
which regions are affected,

02:05:01.670 --> 02:05:04.680
how was the signal processing disrupted,

02:05:04.680 --> 02:05:06.060
which is still a hypothesis,

02:05:06.060 --> 02:05:08.650
but how it's disrupted could tell us a lot

02:05:08.650 --> 02:05:12.310
about maybe there's a resonant point

02:05:12.310 --> 02:05:14.320
at which there's an optimal effect

02:05:14.320 --> 02:05:17.200
when you take a particular
breathing practice.

02:05:17.200 --> 02:05:20.664
And then when we talked about the fact

02:05:20.664 --> 02:05:23.060
that different breathing practices

02:05:23.060 --> 02:05:25.410
could be affecting the outcomes

02:05:25.410 --> 02:05:27.490
through different pathways.

02:05:27.490 --> 02:05:31.700
You have the olfactory pathway,
you have a central pathway,

02:05:31.700 --> 02:05:35.450
you have a vagal pathway, you
have a descending pathway,

02:05:35.450 --> 02:05:40.450
how different practices may change

02:05:41.433 --> 02:05:43.040
the summation of those things

02:05:43.040 --> 02:05:46.430
because I think all those
things are probably involved,

02:05:46.430 --> 02:05:49.420
and we're just beginning
to scratch the surface.

02:05:49.420 --> 02:05:54.420
And I just hope that we can
get serious neuroscientists

02:05:55.370 --> 02:05:59.390
and psychologists to do
the right experiments

02:05:59.390 --> 02:06:00.720
to get at this because I think

02:06:00.720 --> 02:06:05.150
there's a lot of value
to human health here.

02:06:05.150 --> 02:06:07.150
- I do too, and it's one
of the reasons my lab

02:06:07.150 --> 02:06:09.130
has shifted to these
sorts of things in humans.

02:06:09.130 --> 02:06:10.871
I'm delighted that you're continuing

02:06:10.871 --> 02:06:13.609
to do the hardcore
mechanistic work in mice

02:06:13.609 --> 02:06:17.442
and probably do work in
humans already as well,

02:06:17.442 --> 02:06:18.870
if you're not already.

02:06:18.870 --> 02:06:20.690
And there are other
groups, Epel Lab at UCF,

02:06:20.690 --> 02:06:23.258
and a number of, I'm starting
to see some papers out there

02:06:23.258 --> 02:06:25.560
about respiration in humans a little bit,

02:06:25.560 --> 02:06:26.883
some more brain imaging.

02:06:28.670 --> 02:06:32.960
I can't help but ask about
a somewhat unrelated topic,

02:06:32.960 --> 02:06:36.175
but it is important in
light of this conversation

02:06:36.175 --> 02:06:37.790
because you're here,

02:06:37.790 --> 02:06:40.550
and one of the things that I really enjoy

02:06:40.550 --> 02:06:43.450
about conversations with you as it relates

02:06:43.450 --> 02:06:47.253
to health and neuroscience
and so forth is that,

02:06:48.770 --> 02:06:51.160
you're one of the few colleagues I have

02:06:51.160 --> 02:06:56.160
who openly admits to
exploring supplementation.

02:06:56.190 --> 02:06:59.857
I'm a long time supplement fan.

02:07:02.440 --> 02:07:04.800
I think there's power in compounds,

02:07:04.800 --> 02:07:09.370
both prescription, non-prescription,
natural, synthesized.

02:07:09.370 --> 02:07:11.530
I don't use these haphazardly,

02:07:11.530 --> 02:07:13.710
but I think there's
certainly power in them.

02:07:13.710 --> 02:07:15.880
And one of the places
where you and I converge

02:07:15.880 --> 02:07:18.280
is in terms of our interest
in the nervous system

02:07:18.280 --> 02:07:22.910
and supplementation is
vis-a-vis magnesium.

02:07:22.910 --> 02:07:26.980
Now, I've talked endlessly on the podcast

02:07:26.980 --> 02:07:29.940
and elsewhere about
magnesium for sake of sleep,

02:07:29.940 --> 02:07:31.560
and improving transit transitions

02:07:31.560 --> 02:07:33.180
to sleep and so forth.

02:07:33.180 --> 02:07:37.710
But you have a somewhat
different interest in magnesium

02:07:37.710 --> 02:07:39.520
as it relates to cognitive function

02:07:39.520 --> 02:07:41.920
and durability of cognitive function.

02:07:41.920 --> 02:07:43.480
Would you mind just sharing
with us a little bit

02:07:43.480 --> 02:07:46.310
about what that interest
is, where it stems from,

02:07:46.310 --> 02:07:49.730
and because it's The Huberman Podcast,

02:07:49.730 --> 02:07:51.549
and we often talk about supplementation,

02:07:51.549 --> 02:07:54.760
what you do with that information.

02:07:54.760 --> 02:07:55.804
- So, I need to disclose

02:07:55.804 --> 02:07:58.550
that I am a scientific advisor

02:07:58.550 --> 02:08:00.310
to a company called Neurocentria,

02:08:00.310 --> 02:08:04.393
which my graduate student,
Guosong Liu is CEO.

02:08:06.120 --> 02:08:09.160
So that said, I can give
you some background.

02:08:09.160 --> 02:08:12.156
Guosong, although when he was
in my lab worked on breathing,

02:08:12.156 --> 02:08:15.720
had a deep interest in
learning and memory.

02:08:15.720 --> 02:08:16.870
And when he left my lab,

02:08:16.870 --> 02:08:17.990
he went to work for it

02:08:17.990 --> 02:08:22.990
with a renowned learning memory
guy at Stanford, Dick Chen.

02:08:23.060 --> 02:08:26.300
And when he finished there,

02:08:26.300 --> 02:08:29.400
he was hired by Susumu Tonegawa at MIT.

02:08:29.400 --> 02:08:31.220
- Who also knows a thing
or two about memory.

02:08:31.220 --> 02:08:32.053
I'm teasing.

02:08:32.053 --> 02:08:35.530
Susumu Tonegawa has a Nobel for
his work on immunoglobulins,

02:08:35.530 --> 02:08:38.580
but then is a world-class
memory researcher.

02:08:38.580 --> 02:08:41.163
- Yeah, and more.

02:08:42.350 --> 02:08:43.565
- He's many things.

02:08:43.565 --> 02:08:48.565
- And Guosong had very
curious, very bright guy,

02:08:48.590 --> 02:08:52.029
and he was interested in how signals

02:08:52.029 --> 02:08:54.600
between neurons get strengthened,

02:08:54.600 --> 02:08:58.120
which is called long-term
potentiation or LTP.

02:08:58.120 --> 02:09:01.740
And one of the questions that arose

02:09:01.740 --> 02:09:06.740
was if I have inputs to
a neuron and I get LTP,

02:09:08.740 --> 02:09:13.740
is the LTP bigger if the signal is bigger

02:09:13.810 --> 02:09:16.090
or the noise is less?

02:09:16.090 --> 02:09:19.260
So, we can imagine that when
we're listening to something,

02:09:19.260 --> 02:09:21.200
if it's louder, we can hear it better.

02:09:21.200 --> 02:09:23.480
Or if this less noise,
we can hear it better.

02:09:23.480 --> 02:09:26.320
And he wanted to investigate this.

02:09:26.320 --> 02:09:31.320
So I did this in tissue
culture of hippocampal neurons,

02:09:31.360 --> 02:09:35.466
and what he found was that if he lowered

02:09:35.466 --> 02:09:38.863
the background activity
in all of the neurons,

02:09:40.220 --> 02:09:44.600
that the LTP he elicited got stronger,

02:09:44.600 --> 02:09:47.560
and the way he did that was increasing

02:09:47.560 --> 02:09:50.660
the level of magnesium
in the bathing solution.

02:09:50.660 --> 02:09:54.970
This gets into some
esoteric electrophysiology,

02:09:54.970 --> 02:09:57.850
but basically there's a background level

02:09:57.850 --> 02:10:01.080
of noise in all neurons,

02:10:01.080 --> 02:10:04.920
and that part of it is
regulated by the degree

02:10:04.920 --> 02:10:07.750
of magnesium in the extracellular bath.

02:10:07.750 --> 02:10:10.570
- And you mean electrical noise.

02:10:10.570 --> 02:10:12.925
- Electrical noise, I'm
sorry, electrical noise.

02:10:12.925 --> 02:10:17.925
And if you, in what's called
the physiological range,

02:10:18.450 --> 02:10:22.700
which is between 0.8 and 1.2 millimolar,

02:10:22.700 --> 02:10:24.280
which don't worry about the number.

02:10:24.280 --> 02:10:25.430
- I can't believe you
remember the millimolar

02:10:25.430 --> 02:10:26.370
of the magnesium.

02:10:26.370 --> 02:10:28.850
- Well, I'm always frightened that I get,

02:10:28.850 --> 02:10:31.060
I say micro or femto or something,

02:10:31.060 --> 02:10:33.510
I go off by several orders of magnitude,

02:10:33.510 --> 02:10:37.830
but so in that physiological range,

02:10:37.830 --> 02:10:40.800
there's a big difference
in the amount of noise

02:10:40.800 --> 02:10:43.540
in a neuron between
0.8 and 1.2 millimolar.

02:10:44.530 --> 02:10:47.200
So, he played around with the magnesium,

02:10:47.200 --> 02:10:50.720
and he found out that when
the magnesium was elevated,

02:10:50.720 --> 02:10:52.690
it was more LTP.

02:10:52.690 --> 02:10:55.090
All right, that's an
observation in a tissue culture.

02:10:55.090 --> 02:10:56.170
- Right, and I should just mention

02:10:56.170 --> 02:10:58.570
that more LTP essentially translates

02:10:58.570 --> 02:11:00.220
to more neuro-plasticity,

02:11:00.220 --> 02:11:03.620
more rewiring of connections in essence.

02:11:03.620 --> 02:11:08.620
- So, he tested this
in mice and basically,

02:11:10.030 --> 02:11:11.473
he offered them a,

02:11:14.250 --> 02:11:15.240
he had control mice,

02:11:15.240 --> 02:11:16.970
which got a normal diet and one that had,

02:11:16.970 --> 02:11:18.800
one enriched in magnesium,

02:11:18.800 --> 02:11:22.280
and the ones that lived
enriched with magnesium

02:11:22.280 --> 02:11:25.458
had higher cognitive
function, lived longer,

02:11:25.458 --> 02:11:29.130
everything you'd want in some magic pill,

02:11:29.130 --> 02:11:31.150
those mice did that.

02:11:31.150 --> 02:11:32.533
Excuse me, rats.

02:11:34.980 --> 02:11:38.980
The problem was that you
couldn't imagine taking this

02:11:38.980 --> 02:11:43.700
into humans because most magnesium salts

02:11:43.700 --> 02:11:47.790
don't passively get from the
gut into the bloodstream,

02:11:47.790 --> 02:11:49.040
into the brain.

02:11:49.040 --> 02:11:52.710
They pass via what's called a transporter.

02:11:52.710 --> 02:11:54.910
Transporter is something in a membrane

